{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Ring Final Circuit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A power circuit that starts and ends at the same point in the consumer unit, forming a continuous loop.",
      "anchor": "Think of it like a circular race track where power can travel in two directions to reach a socket.",
      "misconception": "Believing that any circuit with multiple sockets is automatically a ring circuit."
    },
    {
      "term": "Radial Circuit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A circuit that runs from the consumer unit to the last point of use without returning to the start.",
      "anchor": "Like a dead-end street; the power travels out to the points and stops at the final one.",
      "misconception": "Thinking radial circuits are only for lighting; they are also used for high-power appliances like cookers."
    },
    {
      "term": "SWA (Steel Wire Armoured)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A heavy-duty cable featuring a layer of steel wire for high mechanical protection.",
      "anchor": "The 'armour' allows it to be buried underground or used in industrial areas where it might be struck.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the steel wire is a main power conductor; its primary job is protection and earthing."
    },
    {
      "term": "MICC (Mineral Insulated Copper Clad)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A fire-resistant cable with copper conductors inside a copper sheath, packed with mineral powder insulation.",
      "anchor": "Often called 'pyro,' it is used for emergency systems because it can continue working during a fire.",
      "misconception": "Assuming it is easy to install; it requires specialized seals to prevent moisture from ruining the powder insulation."
    },
    {
      "term": "Trunking",
      "simpleDefinition": "A rectangular enclosure with a removable lid used to protect and organize multiple cables.",
      "anchor": "Like a 'cable highway' on a wall that makes it easy to add or remove wires later.",
      "misconception": "Confusing trunking with conduit; trunking has a removable lid, whereas conduit is a solid tube."
    },
    {
      "term": "Conduit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A protective tube, made of metal or plastic, through which individual cables are pulled.",
      "anchor": "Think of it as a protective 'pipe' for wires, often used in commercial or industrial buildings.",
      "misconception": "Believing that plastic conduit offers the same level of impact protection as steel conduit."
    },
    {
      "term": "Hazardous Environment",
      "simpleDefinition": "A location where there is a high risk of explosion or fire due to the presence of gases, vapors, or dust.",
      "anchor": "Think of a petrol station or a chemical plant where a single spark could be catastrophic.",
      "misconception": "Thinking 'hazardous' just means a place that is generally dangerous to work in, like a construction site."
    },
    {
      "term": "Control Circuit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A circuit used to manage the operation of other equipment rather than providing the main power.",
      "anchor": "Like a light switch or a thermostat; it sends a signal to tell a larger system when to turn on.",
      "misconception": "Thinking control circuits carry the same high current as the power circuits they are controlling."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "A ring final circuit forms a continuous loop back to the source.",
    "Radial circuits run in a single line to the final point.",
    "SWA provides mechanical protection for industrial environments.",
    "MICC is used for fire-resistant applications.",
    "Trunking is a rectangular enclosure with a removable lid.",
    "The wiring system must be selected to match the environmental stress."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Ring and radial are not interchangeable terms for power delivery.",
    "Industrial and hazardous environments have different specific wiring requirements.",
    "Data and control circuits operate on different principles than standard power circuits."
  ]
}

[
  {
    "title": "Circuit Types and Principles",
    "objective": "Describe the principles of operation for standard circuit types including lighting, power, and specialized circuits.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In electrical installations, we categorize circuits based on how they deliver power to the equipment. A Radial Circuit is the most straightforward design; it runs from the consumer unit to the last point of use, much like a dead-end street. These are commonly used for lighting or high-power individual appliances like cookers. In contrast, a Ring Final Circuit forms a continuous loop, starting and ending at the same point in the consumer unit. This allows power to travel in two directions to reach a socket, which effectively shares the load across the conductors.",
      "Beyond standard power delivery, we use specialized circuits for specific tasks. A Control Circuit is used to manage the operation of other equipment rather than providing the main power; think of a thermostat telling a boiler when to turn on. We also install data communication circuits for networking and emergency circuits for fire alarms or exit lighting. Each circuit type is chosen based on whether it needs to provide a continuous loop of power, a single line of supply, or a control signal."
    ],
    "hint": "Focus on the difference between a loop that returns to the source and a single line that ends at the last point."
  },
  {
    "title": "Wiring Systems and Environments",
    "objective": "Identify appropriate wiring systems for domestic, commercial, industrial, agricultural, and hazardous environments.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Selecting a wiring system depends on the environmental stresses it will face. In domestic settings, we often use flat profile cables. However, industrial sites require heavy-duty protection like SWA (Steel Wire Armoured) cable, which uses a layer of steel wire to prevent mechanical damage. For fire-critical areas, we use MICC (Mineral Insulated Copper Clad) cable. Often called 'pyro,' this cable is fire-resistant because it uses mineral powder insulation and a copper sheath, allowing it to function during a fire.",
      "To house and protect these cables, we use enclosures. Trunking is a rectangular enclosure with a removable lid, acting like a 'cable highway' for multiple wires. Conduit is a solid protective tube, made of metal or plastic, through which individual cables are pulled. In a Hazardous Environment, where explosive gases or dust are present, systems must be specifically sealed to prevent sparks. Agricultural environments also require specialized systems to resist moisture and chemical corrosion from livestock, proving that the environment dictates the choice of materials."
    ],
    "hint": "Consider the specific protection needed, such as fire resistance for MICC or mechanical strength for SWA."
  }
]

